Hmm, right. It's difficult to get into the details here, also given byte ordering for differently sized pointer types and what not. But given that we use the same `memcpy` byte mapping in and out, it should be fine. Let's align the variable names in both functions to make this more clear.

```suggestion
    __Pyx_generic_func_pointer funcptr;
    if (sizeof(funcptr) > sizeof(void*) || __Pyx_TEST_large_func_pointers) {
        result = *((__Pyx_generic_func_pointer*)data);
    } else {
        memcpy((void*)&funcptr, (void*)&data, sizeof(funcptr));
    }
    return funcptr;
```

I'd actually rather expect function pointers to be smaller than data pointers (if they are different at all). Code is fairly unlikely to appear in masses similar to that of today's data.

